  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements designed to combat money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for preventing money laundering\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)\n\n3. The Palermo Convention, which requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision guidelines\n\n5. UN Convention Against Corruption\n\nThese frameworks require countries to:\n- Implement strict banking regulations\n- Report suspicious financial transactions\n- Criminalize money laundering activities\n- Cooperate in international investigations\n- Establish legal mechanisms to trace and seize illicit funds\n\nMany countries have national laws that align with these international standards, such as the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and similar legislation in European countries.\n\nFinancial institutions are typically required to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Monitor and report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain detailed transaction records\n- Implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\nWhile enforcement varies, these international laws provide a framework for combating financial crimes globally.",
